Let $k_1+k_2=k$, where $k, k_1$ are all positive integers with $k_1 \ge 1$. Also let $K=\min\{k_1, \lfloor k_2/9 \rfloor +1\}$. Define $g(x)=\max\{1 \le i \le k: \lfloor i/9 \rfloor +1=x\}, x=1, \ldots, K$.  Define for $x=1, \ldots, K$ that 
\begin{align*}
f(x)=\dfrac{\lfloor 0.1(x+g(x)) \rfloor +1}{k-x+\lfloor 0.1(x+g(x)) \rfloor +1}
\end{align*} I would like to show that $f(x)/x$ is nondecreasing for $x=1,\ldots, K$. Can anyone give some hint?

Data I have three $N \times N$ complex hermitian matrices $A=xx^{H}$,$R=rr^{H}$ and a positive-definite matrix $B$. Here $x$ and $r$ are two $N \times 1$ complex vectors. Let $\lambda_{i}, 1\leq i\leq N$ denotes the N eigenvalues of B which are also positive. Clearly $A$ and $R$ are two rank one positive semi-definite matrices. $B$ is invertible. What I need to find What is the largest eigenvalue of the GEVP? \begin{align}
(A\otimes R)v=\gamma (B\otimes R)v
\end{align} Will the maximum eigenvalue be (seemingly nice) $||r||^{2}x^{H}B^{-1}x$? What I know Consider the generalized Eigenvalue problem (GEVP)
\begin{align}
Av=\gamma Bv
\end{align}
Since $B$ is invertible, this is equivalent to find the eigenvalues of $B^{-1}A$, in fact , since $A$ is rank one matrix, there is only one eigenvalue which will be positive, and it will be given by $x^{H}B^{-1}x$ ($A=xx^{H}$). Now I am interested in the matrices, $A \otimes R$ and $B \otimes R$ which are $N^{2} \times N^{2}$ in dimension. Now $A \otimes R$ is a rank one matrix, and its only non-zero eigenvalue is $||x||^{2}||r||^{2}$. $B \otimes R$ is a positive semi-definite matrix with $N$ of its eigenvalues being $\lambda_{i}||r||^{2}, 1\leq i \leq N$ and rest of the $N^{2}-N$ eigenvalues being zero.

