u_1$, $
u_2$ two probability measures on it. For $i=1,2$, let $L_{
u_i}:L^{1}(
u_i)ightarrow\mathbb R$ be the map defined by $L_{
u_i}(g)=\int_\Omega gd
u_i$. Denote by $[1_E]_{
u_i}$ the equivalence class in $L^1(
u_i)$ of the characteristic function $1_E$. Does there always exist a linear map $M:L^1(
u_1)ightarrow L^1(
u_2)$ such that $$L_{
u_2}\circ M([1_E]_{
u_1})=L_{
u_1}([1_E]_{
u_1})$$ for all $E\in\Sigma$?
When $
u_1$ is absolutely continuous to $
u_2$ then, by the Radon-Nykodim Theorem, the map $M$ can be given explicitly, i.e. there exists a $\Sigma$-measurable function $f:\Omegaightarrow\mathbb R$, such that $M(g):=f\cdot g$ will satisfy the equation given above. So the question becomes interesting when $
u_1$ and $
u_2$ are singular to each other, and the spaces $L^1(
u_1)$ and $L^1(
u_2)$ are not isometric. I posted this question also on MO .

